AGI -&nbsp;King Harald of Norway resumed its functions after more than two and a half months of break for health problems, with a reduced agenda due to the advanced age. Harald, 87, is the oldest monarch in Europe and was hospitalized after a private trip to Malaysia at the end of February.<br> The sovereign was repatriated on a medical flight and a permanent pacemaker was installed to replace a temporary device placed by doctors in Malaysia.
&nbsp;
"His Majesty the King is happy to be back and resume his functions," reads in a note of Palazzo.<br> "The king will adapt in the future his program, taking into account his age," the royal house reported, specifying that it will proceed to "a permanent reduction of the number and intensity of his activities". Harald, on the throne since 1991, has suffered several health problems in recent years, but has excluded abdicating. During his absences he was replaced by the Crown Prince, the fifty-year-old Haakon.&nbsp;

